author: @udaylunawat2163
text: @6:45 Scaling is unnecessary since the base learners in XGBoost are trees, and any monotonic function of any feature variable will have no effect on how the trees are formed.   In general, algorithms that exploit distances or similarities (e.g. in form of scalar product) between data samples, such as k-NN and SVM, are sensitive to feature transformations.   Graphical-model based classifiers, such as Fisher LDA or Naive Bayes, as well as Decision trees and Tree-based ensemble methods (RF, XGB) are invariant to feature scaling, but still it might be a good idea to rescale/standardize your data.   "On the regression tasks, it is sensible to normalize targets so that the average becomes zero since regularization shrinks towards zero."
